In HTTPS connections, the client establishes a secure channel with the server using TLS. It does so by verifying the server’s SSL/TLS Certificate.

There are three aspects involved in certificate validation; 

1. The Certificate itself needs to be valid
2. The server needs to be the same as the domain name associated with that certificate
3. The CA issuing the certificate must be considered trustworthy by a "trust store", i.e. the list of known trustable CAs stored in the client's security context.

An overview of the process is shown here:

[![enter image description here]](https://i.stack.imgur.com/Mm2Jz.png)

For example, this is how you would verify a server Certificate in Java:

```
String[] chain = new String[] {"subjectDN", "issuerDN", "not Before", "not
After", "subjectPublicKeyInfo", "signatureAlgorithm"};
CertificateFactory cf = CertificateFactory.getInstance("X.509");
X509Certificate cert = null;
try {
        cert = (X509Certificate) cf.generateCertificate(inputStream);
        // verify the certificate
        if (verifyCertificate(cert, chain)) {
            // valid; do what you need to do with the cert
        } else {
            // invalid; do something here
        }
    } catch (CertificateException ex) {
        // ex.printStackTrace();
    }

```

