def comb_sort(list1):
    gap = len(list1)
    shrinked = True
    while gap != 0 or shrinked:
        if gap > 1:
            gap = int(gap / 1.3)
            shrinked = True
        else:
            gap = 1
            shrinked = False
        i = 0
        while i + gap < len(list1):
            if list1[i] > list1[i + gap]:
                list1[i], list1[i + gap] = list1[i + gap], list1[i]
                shrinked = True
            i += 1
    return list1

def find_Volume(base, height_height, depth):
    import math
    area = height_height * base / 2
    volume = area * depth
    return math.floor((volume * 10 + 0.5) / 10)

A race condition occurs when two or more threads share the same resource and one thread can modify that resource while the other thread is reading or modifying it. This typically occurs when two or more threads access shared memory or synchronize with each other.

A mutex provides mutual exclusion, meaning that only one thread can execute certain code at one time. This prevents race conditions by controlling access to the shared environment of two or more threads, thereby ensuring consistency of the shared resources against parallel execution. 
The following are some examples of mutexes:

- POSIX threads: POSIX PTHREAD_MUTEX locks the mutex so that only one thread at a time can use the critical resource.
- Visual Studio: Critical Section
- .NET: Monitor, Lock(), Enter(), Exit().

These mutexes ensure that two or more threads can not execute a specific section of code at the same time. This makes sure that the execution of two or more threads are predictable and consistent.  
Locking a mutex allows the code inside the critical-section to run uninterrupted by the other code threads. Any code thread trying to lock the mutex during the critical section will be blocked until the section becomes available. 
This can be represented as follows: 

Mutex mutexLock;

void function()
{
  // Acquire the mutex
  mutexLock.lock();
  // Do the work

  // Release the mutex
  mutexLock.unlock();
}  
